image.altText: A man smiles with short brown hair wears a green and gold jersey, he sits in front of computer with map open

props.synopsis: For the next seven months, Oscar Pearce is hoping to spend about eight hours per day guessing where he is in the world, but from his computer.

title.children: GeoGuessr Oscar Pearce prepares to return to global competition to represent Australia

image.altText: housing estate shot from a drone

props.synopsis: House prices are on track to rise across the country, propelled by renters and migrants wanting to buy their own homes and buyers trying to get in ahead of interest rate cuts expected later this year.

title.children: House prices likely to keep going up in 2024 due to forecast rate cuts, migrant boom

image.altText: Two women embrace outside a burnt building.

props.synopsis: Many Israelis say that they will never forgive Palestinians for what Hamas did. It's this "never forgiving" that puts the two sides further apart than ever in this decades-old conflict, writes John Lyons.

title.children: Jump on a plane to Israel and you'll see one of the enduring ways life has changed since October 7

image.altText: Celeste Manno.

props.synopsis: As Victoria's Supreme Court prepares to sentence obsessed killer Luay Sako, experts say stalking remains an "epidemic" that authorities are struggling to contain.

title.children: As a court prepares to sentence Celeste Manno's obsessive killer, experts say there are many more just like him

image.altText: An Indigenous woman with long, silver hair stands in front of a rocky beach.

props.synopsis: The First Nations people of the Eyre Peninsula are threatening legal action against SA Water to stop the construction of a desalination plant they say will cause "insurmountable damage" to fish traps that predate colonisation.

title.children: First Nations group threatens to sue SA Water over $313m desalination plant scheme

image.altText: A woman holds a medical syringe and a small bottle labelled "Coronavirus COVID-19 vaccine"

props.synopsis: A South Australian government employee who fell ill after getting a mandatory COVID vaccine has won compensation against his employer.

title.children: Tribunal orders compensation for SA government employee who developed pericarditis after COVID jab

image.altText: Paramedics carry a woman on a stetcher

props.synopsis: The hospital informs Ms O'Neill and apologises after it discovers a photo of her injured, unbandaged leg had been shared publicly, in a serious breach of patient privacy.

title.children: St Vincent's Hospital apologises to woman bitten by shark in Sydney Harbour after photo leaked

image.altText: A woman with a neutral expression looks at the camera.

props.synopsis: When British post offices introduced a new accounting system more than two decades ago, money started going missing — what happened next has been described by some as the country's biggest ever miscarriage of justice.

title.children: 'They were like the mafia': When money went missing from post offices, everyone was looking in the wrong place

image.altText: A man in an orange tie and a black and white suit stands at a podium.

props.synopsis: After unveiling his re-jigged tax plan last week, Anthony Albanese has conducted five press conferences, eight radio interviews and two TV interviews — the kind of media blitz usually reserved for winning an election, writes David Speers.

title.children: Albanese is on a Stage 3 tax cuts media blitz. The upcoming byelection will tell us if it's worked

image.altText: Dozens of tractors, harvesters and trucks lined the street outside the Renmark Hotel on a sunny day.

props.synopsis: Growers in Australia's largest wine grape producing region are calling for more government support, along with a mandatory code of conduct, to ensure the sustainability of their industry, as many let their fruit rot due to below-cost prices.

title.children: Wine grape growers drive tractors through Riverland streets in protest against below-cost prices

image.altText: Israeli drone in Gaza

props.synopsis: Approvals to export Australian made military equipment to Israel are being "stalled" by the Albanese government as concerns grow over the rising number of civilian casualties in Gaza.

title.children: Australia 'stalls' military export requests from Israel over Gaza war concerns — growing number of civilian casualties

image.altText: Women sitting stares toward into distance, with trees and building in background.

props.synopsis: Survivors of institutional childhood sexual abuse have launched a class action against one of Australia's most prominent sexual abuse law firms, which they say failed to obtain proper compensation from the institutions responsible for their abuse.

title.children: Sexual abuse survivors turn on their lawyers, alleging negligence in class action lawsuit

image.altText: Close-up of a green Medicare card with a calculator and money in the background

props.synopsis: Disadvantaged areas have recorded among the highest increase in bulk-billed GP appointments since the government tripled the Medicare incentive in November, but for those who don’t qualify the cost remains a significant barrier.

title.children: Bulk billed GP appointments rise, but access remains a challenge

image.altText: Ange Postecoglou gestures

props.synopsis: Ange Postecoglou's Spurs look to re-enter the Premier League's top four when they host a Brentford side that has just ended a seven match winless run in all competitions. Follow live.

title.children: Spurs trail combative Brentford in bid to go fourth in Premier League table

image.altText: A collection of old photos of people celebrating Lotto wins.

props.synopsis: Australians are readying for the country's biggest ever Lotto jackpot, but the astronomical odds of winning have prompted experts to issue warnings to people dreaming of striking it rich.

title.children: Dreaming of claiming tonight's $200m Lotto jackpot? Experts say you're more likely to suddenly drop dead

image.altText: A blonde woman smiling and holding a cavoodle.

props.synopsis: Lucy Walton is among many Australian women investigating fertility testing in the so-called panic years. But experts warn against cheap, at-home testing kits.

title.children: More women like Lucy are testing their fertility but some experts are questioning if it's worth it

image.altText: A man and woman standing in front of a unit construction site

props.synopsis: Julia and Matthew Mooney thought they'd be celebrating the New Year in their new unit on Queensland's Sunshine Coast. Instead, the couple is back to square one in their property search.

title.children: Couple call for changes to sunset clause laws after contract for dream unit terminated by developer

image.altText: Train track with metro line next to it.

props.synopsis: A New South Wales Greens MP says many documents relating to Sydney Metro contracts remain privileged despite to highly paid contractors at the centre of allegations relating to the project being replaced.

title.children: Highly paid Sydney Metro contractors 'replaced' in wake of 'serious' allegations

image.altText: A firefighter surrounded by burning trees,

props.synopsis: Traditional fire management strategies such as hazard reduction burns, logging, and the thinning of undergrowth have increased the flammability of forests, new research has found.

title.children: Hazard reduction burns increase risk of severe bushfires, report finds

image.altText: An Australian cricketer smiles on stage as he wears a medal around his neck.

props.synopsis: Ash Gardner adds the Belinda Clark Medal to her player of the T20 World Cup award, and comeback kid Mitch Marsh's huge year is capped with him winning the Allan Border Medal at the Australian Cricket Awards.

title.children: Mitch Marsh wins Allan Border Medal, Ash Gardner takes out Belinda Clark Medal

image.altText: Judges at top UN court.

props.synopsis: Judges at the top UN court finds that Russia violated elements of a UN anti-terrorism treaty, but declined to rule on allegations brought by Kyiv that Moscow was responsible for the shooting down of Malaysia Airlines flight MH17 over eastern Ukraine in 2014.

title.children: UN court rejects most of Ukraine's 'terror' case against Russia, no ruling on shooting down of flight MH17

image.altText: cash lays on a kitchen table beside a cup of tea and a list of bills owing

props.synopsis: The record high tops the August 2021 record, and reinforced expectations of RBA rate cuts in the second of half of 2024.

title.children: Australian share market surges to an all-time high, lifted by lower than expected inflation data

image.altText: Workers make dog treats at a factory in Melbourne.

props.synopsis: Inflation comes in lower than expected, with prices rising just 0.6 per cent over the December quarter and 4.1 per cent over the past year.

title.children: Inflation may be falling fast with rates set to follow, but people like Ash and Rebecca are still struggling

image.altText: Composite of two mazda cars.

props.synopsis: The fault affects the gear set within the power steering assembly and increases "the risk of an accident causing injury or death", the recall notice says.

title.children: Thousands of Mazda cars recalled over a potentially deadly manufacturing defect

image.altText: Swift parrot perched on a tree branch.

props.synopsis: Environmentalist Bob Brown's foundation is challenging the legality of logging at a forestry coupe in the Huon Valley, south of Hobart.

title.children: Judge orders logging suspension in area of Tasmania home to rare swift parrot

image.altText: A man in military uniform hugging another man.

props.synopsis: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy says 207 captured Ukrainian soldiers are back home after the prisoner swap.

title.children: Russia and Ukraine exchange prisoners of war a week after Russian military plane was shot down

image.altText: Imran Khan wearing a black shirt speaks as he raises his left hand up palm upwards

props.synopsis: Khan and his wife had been accused of retaining and selling state gifts when the former premier was in power.

title.children: Pakistan's former prime minister Imran Khan and wife sentenced to 14 years in prison for corruption

image.altText: Police tape marks off the boat of a police boat.

props.synopsis: A teenager is charged with manslaughter and three others with aggravated robbery following a 27-year-old man's drowning during an alleged attempt to steal a handbag.

title.children: Teen charged with manslaughter over man's drowning during alleged robbery

image.altText: A Queensland State of Origin coaching staff member holds a ball as he points on the field during a training session.

props.synopsis: The Maroons' tilt at a third-straight State of Origin series win will go on without Queensland great Cameron Smith, who has stepped down from his assistant coaching role under Billy Slater.

title.children: Cameron Smith steps down from Maroons assistant coaching role

image.altText: Powerlines silhouetted by the sun.

props.synopsis: Queensland’s state-owned power grid quietly forced almost 170,000 air-conditioners in homes and businesses into low-power mode six times over summer.

title.children: Almost 170,000 air conditioners remotely turned down six times during blistering summer heat

image.altText: Composite image of Drake looking sad and a phone screen with the tiktok app open

props.synopsis: Songs by Taylor Swift, Drake, Billie Eilish and more could vanish from the platform after one of the world's biggest record labels slammed TikTok over "bully" tactics in an open letter.

title.children: Universal Music Group pulls music from TikTok, citing 'bullying' and 'bad deal' for artists

image.altText: A man leaning against a wall of wooden alcohol barrels.

props.synopsis: More than half the cost of a bottle of spirits goes to the tax office. Distillers want a two-year pause on the "outrageous" excise, but the Alcohol and Drug Foundation says it's necessary to stop harmful drinking.

title.children: Distillers push for pause as spirit excise increases make favourite tipple more expensive

image.altText: Sydney woman Lauren O'Neill in a priofile photo

props.synopsis: Lauren O'Neill also expressed gratitude for her "heroic and very kind neighbours" who stepped in after she was bitten on the leg by a shark on Monday.

title.children: Woman bitten by shark in Sydney Harbour thanks 'heroic' neighbours

image.altText: A man holds a bunch of bridles.

props.synopsis: A 10-month investigation into Tasmania's harness racing industry has found individuals within the industry engaged in team driving, race fixing and animal abuse.

title.children: 'Dark day for Tasmania's harness racing': Long-awaited report makes findings of race fixing, animal abuse

image.altText: Tall white cloud walls look like a stadium.

props.synopsis: Each year, a team of scientists flies directly into the eyes of some of the world’s biggest storms as they try to solve one of meteorology's greatest forecasting fears — the rapid intensification of life-threatening hurricanes and cyclones.

title.children: As pilots bring this plane up to the wall of the hurricane, it starts to shake like 'an old wooden rollercoaster'
